      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a73ff253d3a51a69",
      "text": "Learning Intentions set the focus for our lessons, what we intend for our learners to explore and discover. In the inquiry classroom, learning intentions are often phrased as questions to position the learning as an investigation. John Hattie, Lynn Sharratt and many others tell us that when we are clear about our intent for learning, our learners are more likely to be successful.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "98852d4837a9b90c",
      "text": "Learning Intentions describe 'the what' of learning, the content focus. A split screen approach to learning intentions also makes explicit 'the how' of learning. Using a split screen develops self-awareness in what our learners do, say and think whilst they are learning. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "badab907ce53baa4",
      "text": "Through harnessing the split screen approach to learning intentions, we consciously engage learners in investigating how they learn. Powerful skills and dispositions for learning are noticed and named, modelled and practiced. A split screen positions learners to make connections between learning purpose and learning process. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "557a645f298ed399",
      "text": "A mathematics lesson with a Learning Intention of 'How can we use addition to help us with subtraction?' might be split screened with a communication skill focus of 'How might we effectively communicate our thinking to others? During this lesson, the teacher would design opportunities for learners to practice communicating their thinking in different ways. They would also make effective communication of thinking explicit to learners through noticing and naming and documenting these as Success Criteria. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "20ee61121efb551d",
      "text": "Guy Claxton describes 21st Century skills and dispositions as 'what our children really need to learn'. In his book, Educating Ruby, Claxton identifies seven core character competencies that the education system should seek to develop in learners - Confidence, Communication, Collaboration, Curiosity, Creativity, Commitment and Craftsmanship. It is these skills and dispositions that truly prepare our learners for the world beyond school."
